name: Ask Natural England a question or get advice related to protected sites

components.content:
You should use this form to apply to or consult Natural England for the following types of advice:

* Habitats Regulations Assessment (HRA) advice
* Section 28i Site of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI) advice (also known as statutory consultation), including advice on a felling licence or forestry operations 
* Ask a general protected sites related question

This form should not be used for For Information Only (FIO) submissions.

## For Information Only submissions
Forestry Commission and Environment Agency staff intending to submit For Information Only (FIO) submissions, please email the relevant documents to protectedsites@naturalengland.org.uk.

If you want to fly a drone over a SSSI, your activity may require consent. The landowner or occupier may need to apply to Natural England for consent for the activities you wish to carry out. Natural England cannot provide landowner information, as this would breach the Data Protection Act. 

Public bodies (Section 28G authorities) and the landowner or occupier of a Site of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI) have responsibilities which help protect these sites. 

Members of the public would be breaking the law if they:

* intentionally or recklessly damage the SSSI
* destroy any of the features of special interest
* disturb wildlife for which the site was notified
* carry out listed operations without consent

Natural England can only give consent for an activity on a SSSI to the landowner or occupier. So, if you wish to access or carry out any activities on a SSSI, you must contact the landowner or occupier, or the public body managing the site. 

For further information on [public body SSSI responsibilities](https://www.gov.uk/guidance/sites-of-special-scientific-interest-public-body-responsibilities) 

For further information on [landowner and occupier SSSI responsibilities](https://www.gov.uk/guidance/protected-areas-sites-of-special-scientific-interest )

Landowner or occupier details may be available from [HM Land Registry](https://www.gov.uk/search-property-information-land-registry)


### For more information on drone flying: 

* the [Drone and Model Aircraft Code](https://register-drones.caa.co.uk/individual) includes a brief reference to SSSIs
* [government advice about drones](https://www.gov.uk/government/news/drones-are-you-flying-yours-safely-and-legally) and the guidance and laws surrounding their use
* [Civil Aviation Authority information](https://www.gov.uk/guidance/protected-areas-sites-of-special-scientific-interest) about drone use (may be useful for third parties wishing to discuss consent with owner or occupiers)
* guidance on whether you will need to [apply for a licence for disturbing or removing wildlife or damaging habitats](https://www.gov.uk/guidance/wildlife-licences)
* there might also be local restrictions on drone flying. For example, the use of drones on any common land in [Dartmoor National Park is an offence under the National Park Byelaws](https://www.dartmoor.gov.uk/enjoy-dartmoor/outdoor-activities/drones-and-model-aircraft)
* the [National Trust](https://www.nationaltrust.org.uk/who-we-are/about-us/flying-drones-at-our-places) have a policy of not granting permission for private flying from their land and properties

components.content:
Under Section 28i of the Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981, a Section 28G authority must consult Natural England where it is advising or enabling another party to carry out works likely to damage a SSSI.

However, we encourage Section 28G authorities to consult Natural England when such work is likely to benefit a SSSI. This ensures proposed actions are compatible with the site’s notified features and conservation objectives, and avoids unintended harm.


Examples of nature-positive outcomes include:

* restoring habitats
* improving condition
* enhancing features
* delivering biodiversity net gain, flood or climate outcomes

Local Nature Reserves (LNRs) can only be designated by local authorities. 

If you are interested in creating or managing a Local Nature Reserve, you’ll need to follow the formal process set out by government and consult Natural England as part of the declaration. 

LNRs must be on land that the local authority owns, leases or controls via an agreement with the owner, and the site should have local importance for wildlife, geology, education, or quiet enjoyment of nature. The formal declaration requires a boundary map, a management plan and approval by the relevant authority committees.

[Read more guidance on LNRs here](https://www.gov.uk/guidance/create-and-manage-local-nature-reserves).

If your query relates to something else, you can click the Back link at the top of the page and choose a different option.

pages.title: Designating Sites of Special Scientific Interest (SSSIs)

components.content:
Sites of Special Scientific Interest (SSSIs) are designated only by Natural England when land has wildlife, geological or landform features considered to be of special scientific interest. Natural England assesses the site and notifies (designates) it as an SSSI if it meets the required criteria. 

If you are enquiring about creating or designating a new SSSI, this is not something that landowners, developers, or members of the public can request or apply for directly. The designation process is carried out solely by Natural England, who will contact affected landowners if their land is selected for notification. 

You can [read more about how SSSI designation works](https://www.gov.uk/guidance/protected-areas-sites-of-special-scientific-interest#new-sssi-notifications), including how Natural England selects and notifies new sites.

If your question relates to something else, you can click the Back link at the top of the page and choose a different option.

pages.title: Find out about your responsibilities towards SSSIs

components.content:
## Public bodies and Section 28G authorities
If you’re a public body (or working on behalf of one) you must consider the potential impact of activities and works that you plan to carry out as a public body, or those that are proposed by others that you may consent to, on the interest features of any nearby Site of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI). 

This is part of your general duty as a Section 28G authority, where you must take reasonable steps to conserve and enhance the special features of sites of special scientific interest (SSSIs) when carrying out your statutory duties and giving others permission for works. 

If you decide that works you are to carry out in line with your statutory duties are likely to damage the condition or special features of a SSSI, you must ask for assent from Natural England before carrying out these works. 

For further information on public body SSSI responsibilities and the processes to follow regarding when to request Assent, [see the Gov.uk website](https://www.gov.uk/guidance/sites-of-special-scientific-interest-public-body-responsibilities)


# Find out about Protected Sites

Protected Sites include sites of national and European-level importance, such as:

* [Sites of Special Scientific Interest (SSSI)](https://jncc.gov.uk/our-work/guidelines-for-selection-of-sssis/ )
* [Special Areas of Conservation (SAC)](https://jncc.gov.uk/our-work/special-areas-of-conservation-overview/ )
* [Special Protection Areas (SPA)](https://jncc.gov.uk/our-work/special-protection-areas-overview/ )
* [RAMSAR sites](https://jncc.gov.uk/our-work/ramsar-convention/ )
* [Marine Protection Zones](https://jncc.gov.uk/our-work/marine-conservation-zones/)
* [Nature Conservation Marine Protected Areas](https://jncc.gov.uk/our-work/nature-conservation-mpas/)

Protected sites are designated for their wildlife or geological importance. These sites often overlap, so one area might have multiple designations. You can find out more about these designations and the laws protecting them by selecting the links above. 

If you want to know more about a specific protected site, you can use the [MAGIC mapping system](https://magic.defra.gov.uk/home.htm) to find out their:

* location
* boundaries
* link to its page in Designated Sites View (by selecting the Identify tool and selecting the protected site on the map) 

You can search for detailed information on a specific protected site within Natural England’s remit through the [Designated Sites View website](https://designatedsites.naturalengland.org.uk/).

components.content:
Competent Authorities have a duty to protect, conserve and restore European sites. ‘European sites’ refer to protected sites of European-level importance. If a plan or project might impact on the features of a European site, competent authorities must complete a habitats regulations assessment (HRA). 

Competent Authorities are public bodies, statutory undertakers, statutory nature conservation bodies, Ministers, departments of government and anyone holding public office. 

Please see the [Gov.uk website for information on when this duty applies](https://www.gov.uk/guidance/duty-to-protect-conserve-and-restore-european-sites), when a habitats regulations assessment is needed, and your general duties toward the conservation and restoration of a European site 

We hope that the above helps answer your query. If not, you can continue in this form and ask a specific question, or you can search for information on nature conservation-related subjects. You can also subscribe to the Natural England blog for important announcements and insight into Natural England’s work.
